## Which Web Design Features Actually Help a Writer's Blog

**Do these — they earn their complexity:**

Scroll-triggered fade-ins are the single most powerful. Each piece card appearing as you scroll down feels editorial and intentional. Keep them subtle — 20px of upward drift + opacity, 0.4s, done. Anything more theatrical feels like a portfolio site.

Skeleton loading is worth it specifically on the article grid. Instead of content flashing in or a spinner, the skeleton makes the layout feel stable before content arrives. Readers stay oriented.

Tabs for genre filtering (Essays / Stories / Poems) should feel like flipping to a section of a magazine. Instant, no page reload, with a small animated underline sliding between options.

A reading progress bar at the top of individual essay pages is subtle but genuinely useful — it tells a reader "you're 60% done, keep going." It also signals that the site was crafted thoughtfully.

Sticky header that shrinks on scroll — full masthead at top, then collapses to just your name + nav as you scroll down. Keeps navigation available without eating reading space.

**Skip these for your use case:**

Parallax scrolling feels literary on paper, distracting in practice when the *writing* is supposed to be the experience. Infinite scroll is fine for social media — for essays, paginated archives feel more intentional. Hover card previews are a nice touch but add complexity for uncertain payoff.

