Here's how to read what you're looking at:

The **reading progress bar** (the thin line at the very top of each demo) is 3px tall and lives at the edge of the browser chrome. On an actual article page, it fills as you scroll. It's the kind of thing readers notice without knowing why the site feels polished.

The **tabs** show the sliding-underline pattern. In real implementation, the underline animates with CSS `transition` on the `border-bottom` — no JavaScript needed for the visual, only for the filter logic.

The **skeleton loading** fires when you click "Simulate Load." Notice it holds the exact same column layout as the real cards — that's the key. Skeletons that don't match the incoming content layout feel worse than a plain spinner.

The **scroll-fade items** use `opacity` + `translateY` with staggered `transition-delay` per item. In a real implementation these trigger via `IntersectionObserver` — each card fades up as it enters the viewport, never all at once.

