The **tagline next to your name** shifts from a thesis statement to a confession. "Writes things down" is disarming. It's what C.S. Lewis might actually say at a dinner party if someone asked what he did.

The **"currently" pill** in the nav is one tiny detail that does enormous work. It tells visitors there's a real person here who is mid-thought, not a curator of a finished archive. Swap it seasonally — "currently: avoiding a deadline" or "currently: on page 400 of something long."

The **honest badges** on cards ("mildly ranty," "my favorite so far," "took me three weeks") are author's notes, not metadata. Stephen King does this constantly in his forewords — the small admission that earns enormous trust.

The **pull quote attribution** gets a tail: "written at 11pm." One clause. It places the work in a human moment rather than a vacuum.

The **newsletter copy** swaps "new pieces by email" for "when I finish them — no schedule." That's not lowering expectations, that's setting honest ones. Readers who sign up for that are the readers you actually want.

The whole effect is: the writing still looks serious, the *person* looks approachable. Which is exactly the Lewis/King territory — both were ferociously serious writers who never seemed to take themselves too seriously at all.

